Critics such as the size of the asteroid and the angle of impact are factors that determine the depth of the crater and the damage caused by impact.
Let's take a look at a few scenarios based on the simulation of the European Space Agency.
If a 100 m diameter asteroid hits Earth at a 45-degree angle of 60 km per second, it forms a crater with a depth of about 250 meters and an anchor of 1,200 meters.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake at 6 on the Richter scale, and even if you're 10 kilometers from the impact point, you get third-degree burns.
And those 50 kilometers away will be waiting for shattered window windows.
If an asteroid hits a mile in diameter, it becomes even more depressing.
With the same angle and speed value, if such an asteroid hits Earth, it forms a crater at a depth of about 600 meters and 12 km in diameter.
So a whole neighborhood turns into a crater and disappears instantly.
Even if you're 100 kilometers away from the impact point due to the heat caused by the impact, you get third-degree burns.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake at 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage to the asteroid depends not only on the chemical composition of the asteroid, but also on the rock structure of the region it will hit.
The above values are given based on the scenario that arises if a hard rock-like asteroid falls into an area of sedimentary rocks.
If the asteroid is mostly made up of iron, if it falls on a surface formed by the cooling of lava, the crater size will increase by threefold, and the disaster that arises accordingly will fold.
66 million years ago, something worse happened to the dinosaurs and they were hit by an asteroid about 10 km across.
