In 2003, the area was officially separated as Papua and West Papua, as independent Papua New Guinea would occupy the eastern part of the island.
The enarotali is as remote as it is; the journey here involves a 90-minute flight from the regional capital, Jayapura, to Nabire, and a five-hour drive that shakes the stomach with a rental vehicle.
No public transport.
The 19,000-strong town contains wooden houses fenced with bamboo fences, crumpled iron roofs turned into various yellowish brown tones by rust.
Few Indonesians have traveled here, let alone journalists, and hardly any foreigners have traveled here.
Before the Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago worshipped the Papuans, a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes," Degei said, referring to his vibrant, hand-tied turban, dark shirt and shiny skirt.
