Papua is the poorest region in Indonesia, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have the worst child death and literacy rates in Asia.
But this is also the golden land of Indonesia.
Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is located only 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous area in the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport extracted about $3.1 billion in gold and copper from here.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
However, these riches, a source of misery for the Papuans, allow Indonesia's powerful army to sustain a suffocating presence.
The New York Times' 2005 study reports that Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units from 1998 to 2004, including up to $150,000 in sums given to a single officer.
The Papuans' call for more autonomy threatens this golden spawning chicken and is ruthlessly out of their rights.
More than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969, according to rights advocates.
Mass killings in the mountainous parts of Papua in the 1970s reached genocide figures according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Indonesian police arrested over 3900 peaceful demonstrators in the area only last year.
The Brisbane Archdiocese's 2016 report "We Will Lose Everything" includes testimony of the mesemony, which was committed the previous year, such as illegal executions, torture (according to another report, especially popular with rape and electricity), and the brutal crushing of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to calculate the number of victims every week because there are incidents," says Human Rights Watch's Indonesian researcher Andreas Harsono.
Pressures were increased as Papua's sources brought settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
The region has an 83% Christian population of 3.5 million, but demographics are changing as Muslim immigrants from the crowded Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive for economic purposes.
Javanese warung kiosks sell gado-gados served with peanut sauce mixed with fried chicken and vegetables.
Locals are having a hard time competing.
"The migrants sell chickens and vegetables cheaper in traditional markets than the native Papuans," explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old native of Paniai, who moved to the regional capital Jayapura for business.
"This caused local Papuans, Papua mama-mamas (women) to lose markets."
The Indonesian president Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, promised to solve inequalities and rights violations in Papua in the 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter took the vote of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Panaia, as he moved along the road to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi in anticipation that justice would fulfill our hope that it would be restored," says You.
In fact, Paniai suffered his worst condition only two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children broke through two Indonesian soldiers on the motorcycle while singing Christmas songs in front of a bonfire in Enarotali.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers resented their style and according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and witnesses said that soldiers who had been drinking chased the group and beat them with their rifles' bottoms.
Then one of the soldiers fired on the group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, had been beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire and events escalated the next day.
As many as 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered to demand justice in a football field in front of the local police station and military command center.
They were carrying ceremonial hunting springs and danced the waita dance of Papua's Mee Pago tribe (running in the form of a public and mimicking the bird song).
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police and the military garrison.
As the nerves grew more tense, orders were sent to soldiers via internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them and kill them." An official document seen by TIME, which was not released to the local media, said so.
Yeremias Kayame (56), head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the impending danger and demanded calm by crying out to the crowd to return home.
No one had any intention of listening.
On the porch of the wood house painted with bright colors, he told TIME, "When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist."
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot, but he says the bullet came from the assembled military contractor.
"It was a crowd, many shots fired," he adds.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the attacks, the native Alfius Youw was shot three times.
Like many Indonesians, Yohanes, known only by one name, told TIME negatively, "I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him."
"I saw him die...I kissed him."
Inspector General Yotje Mende, Chief of Police of Papua, told reporters that his officers had only "secured" the outpost because the outpost was under attack.
"When people threaten to kill us, we have to defend ourselves," said Department Director Pudjo Sulistio, a spokesman for Papua police.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many were also injured.
News of the deaths reached Jakarta only the next day.
Jokowi gave an enthusiastic speech in Jayapura three weeks later, stating that he shared the pain of his victim families and promising to solve historical abuses in Papua.
He said, "I want this case resolved immediately so there won't be another one."
Secretary of Security Wiranto said in October 2016 that he had set up a non-judicial mechanism for historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some in the '90s and some in the early 2000s.
The point is that we are determined to solve these violations but we have processes to go through," said the director of the press.
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto stepped back saying there was no plan to establish a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "All will be resolved by the law."
Wiranto, who B.M. accused of "crimes against humanity" over 1,000 deaths during East Timor's bloody independence vote in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had already been solved.
The families of the Paniai victims met such claims with bitter skepticism.
"I've been interviewed four times in the past three years but there's been no progress," says Yohanes.
"I'm tired."
He says he's still living in fear years later.
He says, "I'm scared."
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the soldier, afraid of getting shot."
His brother Yacobus reiterates the view that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the soldier after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After burying the bodies, the soldier came looking for me," he says.
The attacks haven't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police in Paniai's neighbour Deiyai regency fired on villagers.
