Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned in a nearby lake while fishing, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company's construction site office.
The police said the villagers threw stones at the officers, and they reacted by firing warning shots.
But the locals say that the moving brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd and killed someone.
Dominggu Badii, 29, who lived close to the hospital and witnessed the injuries being raised, tells TIME, "We were so panicked, we were afraid that there would be revenge."
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament called for the officers involved to be held responsible and the moving police brigade to withdraw from the area.
Paniai has always been a troubled area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development feeds the dissatisfaction of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribal peoples, who live scattered along Papua's green mountainous center.
Many joined the rebel army Free Papua Movement (OPM), which claimed to protect the rights of the Papuans by random attacks and by raids of kidnappings on Indonesian soldiers.
Some top OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya, come from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai were arrested and held arbitraryly by the soldier in recent years under the guise of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some of them are never seen again.
Among the Papua peoples, Paniai is known as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds dissatisfaction.
A little rice on sale in Enarotali is too expensive for locals to buy.
The bread is inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly notes, as well as some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women who can sustain four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, selling the rest in the local market.
Ten notes are only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic disparities between local Papuanians and new immigrants who have come in greater numbers since the opening of new air routes to Nabire Airport have grown.
The already underprivileged jobs often go to immigrants who are better educated and richer.
The Papuans rarely have capitalism or necessary qualifications to run their own business competitively.
