The isolation keeps the world's eyes away from Papua.
Furthermore, the limitations of reporting for the international media remain tight.
At the beginning of this year, French journalist Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for "a lack of co-ordination with relevant institutions", despite the rare permission to make videos given to them.
According to Human Rights Watch Asian Deputy Director Phelim Kine, Jokowi's promises to remove and develop news-making restrictions were not carried out to increase election campaign transparency.
In a statement, he said, "There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to make news from the restless eastern end provinces of Indonesia, Papua and West Papua: visa rejection and blacklisting."
The lack of press inspection means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to its neighbors near Papua.
In March, six Pacific nations (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands) encouraged the B.M. Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Panaia attacks.
The same countries historically support the OPM.
"In Indonesia, the democratic system is still valid and there is free media, so the evidence in human rights cases is difficult to cover," said Arrmanatha Nasir, spokesman for the Indonesian Ministry of Foreign Affairs to reporters in Jakarta, ignoring the group's claims.
Locals want more foreign governments interested.
An official delegation from the Netherlands broke its silence when it visited Jayapura on 4 May, headed by the country's human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, according to a source who attended the meeting and did not want its name to be announced, with the locals pleading, "We want freedom."
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but the Papuans say it is unlikely they will ever vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a person with good intentions but is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai attack," says Gobai, head of the tribal council.
