In the Supreme Court, after a fight over funding the drug in the NHS, patients will be able to reach 'translating' HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England has announced that pre-existence prophysics (PREP), a pill taken before sex, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk people by around 86 percent, will be provided by health care to an estimated 10,000 people through a three-year preliminary trial.
He agreed to finance the experiment following the Supreme Court's approval of the Court of Appeals last year, which said the NHS had the power to pay for the PREP, despite allegations that local authorities would finance it.
This move, announced Thursday, was received as a 'new and serious intervention' by the president of NHS England, Simon Stevens, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a 'turn point'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to record the public, with more clinics participating in October, being fully implemented by April 2018 across the UK.
Pre-examination profilerxia (PREP) is a series of HIV drugs that reduce the risk of HIV infection before sex.
Trials showed that the PREP significantly reduced HIV transfer among those at risk of infection.
Getting a PREP before sex means there's enough drugs in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or almost two hours before they have sex.
The appropriate ones for treatment are gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and HIV-positive partners who cannot be successfully treated.
Clinics will determine eligible participants who will consent to the experiment from men, women, transsexual individuals, and those whose partners' HIV status is controlled by an anti-retroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a practitioner will also be able to register for potential participation in participating local sexual health clinics.
The program will hold £10 million, and NHS signed an agreement to provide the drugs this week with an international tender.
The trial was designed to assess the full potential of the PREP by collecting clinical evidence on how the PrEP was targeted, conducted and implemented on a large scale.
