Italy toughens NGOs' approach to immigrant rescue boats
Italy has warned NGOs operating migrant rescue boats in the Mediterranean that they will not be allowed to continue unless they follow new rules affecting their operations.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new charter, it will be difficult to see them continue to operate," Interior Minister Marco Minniti said in an interview with Turin newspaper La Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities were seized on a boat operated by the German charity Jugend Rettet, whose crew suspected that they were actively collaborating with human traffickers in an effort to facilitate illegal immigration.
The charity, which has only been active for a year, refused to comment on the content of detailed accusations against them by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"The saving of human life for us is our top priority and it will be, so we are very sorry that we can't work in the search and rescue area right now," the agency said in a statement on social media.
"Only after we have gathered all the information and have been able to assess the situation can we make an assessment of the charges currently being made."
Italian officials had been monitoring Jugend Rettet's boat, Iuventa, since October.
The crew is suspected to have taken on boats full of rubber immigrants delivered directly to them by human traffickers, allowing smugglers to escape on boats to be used again.
According to the prosecutor's files published by the Italian media, at least one such meeting allegedly took place 1.3 miles off the coast of Libya.
The crew is under suspicion of disregarding the Italian coast guard's authority, which oversees rescue operations in the area due to humanitarian effort rather than any other purpose.
According to the charter, there was supposed to be an Italian police officer on the deck of boats such as Iuventa who was clearly watching their activities.
Only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have so far agreed to comply with the charter: Save The Children, Malta-based MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
