He shared a picture of Brown's lifeless body on the street, which would remain there for four hours.
Ferrell thought to himself, "This is brutal."
But death was nothing new to him or his people.
He left his phone to return to tweets about the gathering of people later that same evening on Canfield Drive.
There were photographs of police tapes, shouting people, and a man holding a banner that said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!", claiming to be Brown's father.
He watched a live broadcast where a police officer was standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another cop, he said, set the trigger on his rifle and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
Ferrell remembered saying, "'It's not usual.'"
"'This isn't the kind of murder we're used to, and it's not typical.'
That's when I felt the chills.
I was angry and crying."
He booked a return ticket and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 a.m., he took his 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided to go with her to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson the next three years will come to the cinemas on 11 August, the subject of a new documentary entitled "Who's the Streets?"
This is a story about survival and protest, love and loss, power and resistance from the point of view of the people who live in that society and fill the streets with the answers they seek.
While Ferrell was driving his vehicle to Ferguson with his daughter, who wore a flowery dress and wore a proper crown to him, they returned to talk about the "experiences of black people and the condition of black people" that they had done over and over again that morning.
He remembered saying, "Do you remember when I taught you that black people should fight for what they believe?"
"We are going to Ferguson now because police killed an 18-year-old boy and that was not true.
I couldn't not take it," Ferrell later said.
"What happened here today... is a consequence of what happened in the past.
He needs to know, see, and grow up in it.
Not only should it develop in the field of activism and organizing, but it also needs to know the layers of its black experience and its black state and its emancipation, it needs to know what we have to do to liberate ourselves.
If I'm lucky enough to give him an experience that he can't experience rude racism personally, he'll be no different than any black woman-child.
I get the feeling that by protecting him from these things, I'm going to be doing him harm."
When they arrived in Ferguson, their first stop was on South Florissant Road, which was across from the police station, where they expected to talk about the matter which later resulted in no criminal charges against officer Darren Wilson, which became a sort of campground for activists.
There Ferrell and his daughter contacted local business owners who prepared packed food.
They packed bags and helped deliver them to the protesters.
A new form of activism was gradually forming for Ferrell.
When he was a student at Missouri State University, he revealed that he was president of the Minority Students' Nurses Association and that he concentrated on injustice in food justice and health in the black community, saying, "My activism has completely changed after August 9th."
"I didn't have any experience with organizing.
It came on its own."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors at an evening screening.
Folayan said that he and his own cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "wanted to make things clear".
Ferrell came up with a question: "Do you want to document it or are you trying to find a story you can use?"
This skepticism had been reported by countless persons, often whites; to come to a society and profit from its pain and resistance...
As Folayan explained in a nearby interview: "We had heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson could not be concentrated, and we decided to do it differently."
Folayan had already made contact with the regional artist Damon Davis, known for his activism regarding prisoners who had been sentenced to death.
His participation warmed Ferrell to the project, as well as six other locals, as well as the team "Who's The Streets?" followed in the years after Brown was shot.
David said, "This documentary isn't someone talking to us or talking to us, it's us."
"That's what was essential to me, how to represent these people because that's how to represent me."
"The goal is not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, but it shows that the move is not "about a masquerading leader, it's about society getting together," Folayan said, while he proved to be the most open of movie participants.
As a result, "Who the Streets?" surprisingly, he documents the personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as his falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt naked," said Ferrell, laughing at his first view of the finished product.
"But when I was doing this and humanizing black people, I knew there could be some sensitivity."
Ferrell's story also cements and re-enters the role of black gay women in the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who derived the slogan #BlackLivesMatter on social media following the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin, identify themselves as gay.
"Black gay women in leadership generally kept the movement going," said Ferrell, "and this is because we are constantly at war on many fronts.
Black gay women have to carry all the weight of it."
Folayan joined this, stating: "The movement is really being held up by black women and many gay black women."
Nevertheless, Ferrell insists that "there is nothing of the kind of action that is happening" and that he was not chosen because of his identities.
He says, "He's the one who triggered this energy."
"But it's not a coincidence that he's on the front lines, because as a black gay woman, there's a lot you can lose by living a life at these intersections.
You can feel his energy on the screen."
Meanwhile, news cameras are long gone in Ferguson, but there are alarming racial connections between the community and the police.
Ferrell is under further surveillance for another 2.5 years due to shutting down the highway during a demonstration.
He defines the socio-political atmosphere in what he calls home as "complexity."
Still, Ferguson keeps track that he carved into his memory three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our job to win.
We have to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains."
