Creating a comic book: The story of a Castle in England
In his recent past, Fort Scotney appeared in a squeeze music video and became a sanctuary for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But right now, Scotney, who inspired a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes of Yorkshire, who had broom hair, a passion for historical documents, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his comfortable seat in the Bewl River valley in Kent.
"I find it very nice to look at the handwriting of someone who's been dead for 300 years."
"What a personal bond it is to hold this letter in my hand."
A Castle in England extending from the Edwardian era to the Middle Ages, each story documents families who lived in Scotney to be illustrated by a different artist (Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg), mentioned from the United Kingdom.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he also wrote Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories in 2014, a project he unexpectedly found emotional, inspired by stories in the British Library.
"Even the fingerprint on the edge of a letter written by a double agent working for King James supporters in the 1700s has brought tears to my eyes," he says.
"This was the mark of his thumb!
And the letters always smell of work because at the time you used to light a fire for the light.
For someone 300 years in the future, that smell feels like it's there.
Oh, I love archives!"
As someone in love with old papers, it seems too good to get support from the National Trust and the Arts Council of England and be able to stay in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I've overstepped my welcome by staying too warm for too long.")
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" fort, scanning archives, and studying many treasures and antiques, such as hyena heads mounted on the walls of the manor and bottles spent centuries in ditches.
He travelled through the lands and ruins of the old castle, speaking to rangers, gardeners, and artists who sometimes worked on illustrations of his book.
And then at night, he'd drink whiskey and start writing.
Since the National Trust could only reach full access when the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died in 2006, Scotney's detailed history is relatively unknown.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only begun to address the archive, which he described as: "For centuries the aristocrats were saying: 'Oh, throw it into the attic'."
The journals, letters from the days of the British empire, maps that set the boundaries of who has what: "You think the land disputes will be boring," Rhodes says, "but there was a birch tree over which the two families had been fighting over.
Forget it, guys!"
Some stories in the collection, including The Labourer, who left the newly built castle to join the Peasant Rebellion in 1381, use the castle as a jumping point to make a wider entrance into British history.
"In this book, Knight Families of Kent and Sussex, there is a record of rebellion in the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
"The Village Rebellion started around here, and I thought a rebellion could be a good starting point.
Maybe these two are connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family who hid a Jesuit priest for seven years during the English Islams.
Or The Smuggler, featuring 18th-century smuggler Arthut Darrell, who is thought to have filled a coffin with stones and staged his own funeral (an exposé made years later when his coffin was exhumed).
The Darrells Rhodes' favorite Scotney family: "These gentlemen seemed to be quite tricky, always going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men solved debt crises by marrying wealthy older women; I imagine them to be a group of handsome men who are capable of courting female heirs."
Rhodes, whose mission at the castle is over, is in search of other singular writing experiences.
In Finnish wildlife, he completed a two-week job for a comic book about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century, which has since been repossessed by nature.
But Scotney has a place in his heart.
He says, "I was sorry I left."
"It's like: 'Oh, now I have to go and face his fucking real life.'"
