The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, testified that immune cells patrol the intestines so that germs hidden in food would not sneak into the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that encourage endurance by maintaining sensitive tissues without harm.
If the balance shifts too much towards inflammation, the inflammation can result from intestinal disease.
Experiments found that a form of immune cell has emerged in mice carrying a specific bacteria in their intestines that promotes durability.
And the bacterium needs triptophane, one of the protein's building blocks, to trigger the cell's emergence.
Professor Colonna said: 'We have connected the bacterium species Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the intestine microbiome, and the development of the cell population that promotes durability.'
